                                <p dir="ltr">Simone Veil was born on July 13, 1927, in Nice, France, into a secular
                                    Jewish family that emphasized education and civic duty. Her childhood was filled
                                    with curiosity and an eagerness to learn, but the peaceful life she knew was soon
                                    shattered by the horrors of World War II.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">In 1944, at just 16 years old, she and her family were arrested by the
                                    Gestapo and deported to Auschwitz‑Birkenau. Her father and brother were sent to the
                                    Baltic states, where they perished, while Simone, her mother, and her sister were
                                    forced to endure the brutalities of the concentration camp. The experience of the
                                    Holocaust left an indelible mark on her, shaping her lifelong dedication to justice,
                                    human dignity, and European unity.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">Despite the trauma, she emerged from the war with resilience, determined to
                                    rebuild her life. She pursued law and political science at the Institut d'Études
                                    Politiques in Paris, where she met and married Antoine Veil, a fellow student.
                                    Together, they navigated post‑war France, where Simone embarked on a career in law
                                    and public service.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">She began her career as a magistrate in the Ministry of Justice, where she
                                    worked on prison reform and the rights of detainees. Her keen sense of justice and
                                    unwavering moral compass quickly set her apart. But it was in the 1970s that she
                                    truly stepped into the public spotlight.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">In 1974, as Minister of Health under President Valéry Giscard d'Estaing,
                                    she spearheaded one of the most controversial legislative battles in French history:
                                    the legalization of abortion. At a time when abortion was illegal and clandestine
                                    procedures led to thousands of deaths, she became the face of a movement that sought
                                    to grant women the right to control their own bodies. Facing virulent opposition,
                                    including sexist and anti‑Semitic attacks, Veil stood her ground with remarkable
                                    courage. Her impassioned speech before the National Assembly, in which she described
                                    the suffering of women forced into unsafe abortions, remains one of the defining
                                    moments of modern French history. The Veil Law was passed in 1975, a landmark
                                    victory for women's rights.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">“</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">Her influence extended far beyond France. In 1979, she became the first
                                    woman to preside over the European Parliament, reinforcing her belief that European
                                    unity was essential to preventing the horrors of war from ever recurring. She
                                    dedicated herself to strengthening European cooperation, championing human rights,
                                    and ensuring that the memory of the Holocaust remained alive so that history would
                                    not repeat itself.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">Throughout her career, Veil continued to advocate for social justice,
                                    immigration rights, and equality. She served on France’s Constitutional Council and
                                    remained an outspoken voice on contemporary issues, always guided by her unwavering
                                    principles.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">Her legacy was cemented in 2008 when she was inducted into the Académie
                                    Française, one of the highest honors in French intellectual life. Upon her death in
                                    2017, she was honored with a state funeral and later interred at the Panthéon,
                                    alongside other great figures of French history—a recognition of her immense
                                    contribution to the nation.</p>

                                <p dir="ltr">Simone Veil’s life was one of extraordinary resilience, courage, and
                                    conviction. From the depths of Auschwitz to the heights of political power, she
                                    never ceased fighting for justice, women’s rights, and European unity. Her story is
                                    a testament to the power of determination and the enduring importance of remembering
                                    history to shape a better future.</p>
